opinion.syllabus:
Insurance, Liability: use of motor vehicle.

A policy issued to the owner of an automobile insured him "against loss or liability growing out of the operation of" the automobile "if it was a pleasure car and not a taxicab and if it was subject to call from the garage only." One, who had been employed by the owner of the automobile, at his direction visited a customer and arranged to take him and a party for a ride to a nearby lake. On the day agreed upon, while such driver, under an arrangement made by him with another person than the defendant's customer, was giving a ride to that person and his companions, he injured a member of the party, who recovered a judgment in an action against the owner of the automobile. In a suit in equity by the person so injured against the owner of the automobile and the insurance company under G.L.c. 214, ยง 3, cl. 10, it was held
that

(1) A finding was warranted that at the time of the accident the automobile was not being operated upon call from the garage;

(2) The circumstances of the accident were not such as to come within the terms of the policy of insurance;

(3) The insurer was not liable either to the owner of the automobile or to the plaintiff.
